Val versus var.

There are two ways to name something in Scala. They look almost identical and behave very differently.

A val is a single-assignment binding. Once it is given a value, the name cannot be re-pointed at a different value. This is the Scala default — reach for it first.

A var is a mutable variable. The name can be reassigned to a different value over its lifetime. Use it deliberately when you actually need a counter, an accumulator, or a state machine — not as a reflex from another language.

The bias is real. Idiomatic Scala uses val for the overwhelming majority of bindings. When new code reaches for var, that should prompt a question — is there a way to express this as a transformation that produces a new value, rather than a mutation that updates an old one.

Two subtleties are worth pinning down now, because both come back later.

First, val locks the binding, not the value it points at. If you bind a val to a mutable object — say a mutable array buffer, or a plain Scala array — the binding is fixed, but the contents of that object can still change in place. The takeaway is that immutability is a property of the type, not of the keyword val.

Second, the right-hand side is evaluated immediately. When you write val x equals some expensive computation, that computation runs at the point of the declaration, not the first time you read x. If you want to defer it, that is a lazy val, which is the next section.
